docs.lead_paragraph: HONG KONG — The Chinese state news media reacted with cautious optimism to former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr.’s victory in the United States presidential election, expressing hope that he would stabilize the fast-deteriorating relations between the two countries.

docs.abstract: The politicization of the ceremonial visit to the Rose Garden by champions is one sign the presidential connection to sports is fraught, maybe inalterably.
docs.snippet: The politicization of the ceremonial visit to the Rose Garden by champions is one sign the presidential connection to sports is fraught, maybe inalterably.
docs.lead_paragraph: Awe and tension filled the air on that sunny afternoon in the Rose Garden four years ago this week. I could feel it, and so could everyone else on hand: The sense of celebration mixed with a gnawing worry for the future.

headline.main: Even With a New President, Sports at the White House Won’t Be the Same
headline.print_headline: Championships Come to Keep Score of a Deepening Divide

docs.abstract: Scenes of jubilation spread minutes after news outlets had called the election for Joseph R. Biden Jr. They lasted into the night.
docs.snippet: Scenes of jubilation spread minutes after news outlets had called the election for Joseph R. Biden Jr. They lasted into the night.
docs.lead_paragraph: CHICAGO — People shouting from their windows, ringing cowbells on their porches and blaring car horns in the streets: As the news spread through cellphones and television screens that Joseph R. Biden Jr. had won the presidential election, spontaneous celebrations erupted within minutes across the nation, and many persisted as street parties into the night.

headline.main: ‘A New Day in America’: Biden Victory Prompts Spontaneous Celebrations
headline.print_headline: ‘New Day’: Ringing Cowbells and Dancing in Streets

byline.original: By Julie Bosman, Sabrina Tavernise and Lucy Tompkins
